  </div>

  <!-- Content sections -->
  <Fragment slot="content">
    <div class="max-w-[1080px] mx-auto px-6 md:px-12 pb-16 space-y-12">
      <!-- How to Use -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="font-heading font-bold text-2xl mb-4">How to Use This Calculator</h2>
        <div class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed space-y-3">
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">1. Fill in each overhead category.</strong> Start with the defaults and adjust to match your actual expenses. Every dollar you spend to keep the business running that is not tied to a specific job belongs here. Open each section and enter your real monthly numbers.</p>
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">2. Set your fleet size.</strong> Enter the number of vans you operate. The calculator multiplies per-van costs (fuel, insurance, maintenance, payments) by your fleet size to get the total fleet overhead.</p>
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">3. Enter your context numbers.</strong> The number of plumbers, billable hours per plumber, annual revenue, daily service calls, and working days let the calculator translate raw overhead into per-hour and per-call figures you can use for pricing.</p>
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">4. Review your results.</strong> Check whether your overhead percentage falls within the 25-35% target range. Use the per-hour and per-call numbers to make sure your billing rates cover overhead plus profit.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- How Overhead Works -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="font-heading font-bold text-2xl mb-4">How Plumbing Overhead Works</h2>
        <div class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed space-y-3">
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">Overhead is every cost that keeps the business running but cannot be billed to a specific job.</strong> It includes rent, vans, insurance, office salaries, software, marketing, and licensing. Unlike materials or plumber labor, overhead does not change based on how many jobs you run in a given week.</p>
          <p>Most plumbing business owners know their overhead exists but have never added it up. That means they are guessing when they set prices. If your overhead is $25,000 per month and you do not know it, you cannot build it into your rates, and every job looks more profitable than it actually is.</p>
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">The per-hour number is the most important output.</strong> It tells you exactly how much overhead you burn for every billable hour a plumber works. If your overhead per hour is $120 and you bill the customer $95 per hour, you are losing money on every call before the plumber even gets paid. Knowing this number forces you to price correctly.</p>
          <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm space-y-1">
            <p>Fleet_Monthly = Vans &times; (Fuel + Insurance + Maintenance + Payment)</p>
            <p>Total_Monthly = Facility + Fleet + Insurance + People + Operations + Compliance + Marketing + Other</p>
            <p>Annual_Overhead = Total_Monthly &times; 12</p>
            <p>Per_Plumber = Annual_Overhead / Number_of_Plumbers</p>
            <p>Per_Hour = Annual_Overhead / (Plumbers &times; Billable_Hours &times; 12)</p>
            <p>Per_Call = Annual_Overhead / (Calls_Per_Day &times; Working_Days &times; 12)</p>
            <p>Overhead_Pct = (Annual_Overhead / Annual_Revenue) &times; 100</p>
          </div>
          <p>The category breakdown shows where your money goes so you can identify the biggest line items. People and fleet are almost always the top two. If marketing is below 6% of revenue, you may be underinvesting in growth.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- When To Use This -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="font-heading font-bold text-2xl mb-4">When To Use This</h2>
        <div class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed space-y-3">
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">Setting billing rates.</strong> Before you decide what to charge per hour or per call, you need to know your overhead per hour. This calculator gives you that number so you can build rates that actually cover your costs and leave room for profit. Without it, you are guessing.</p>
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">Annual budgeting and planning.</strong> At the start of each year, plug in your expected costs to see where you will land. If overhead is creeping above 35% of projected revenue, you know you need to either cut costs or grow revenue before the year gets away from you.</p>
          <p><strong class="text-text-primary">Evaluating growth decisions.</strong> Thinking about adding a van, hiring a dispatcher, or increasing your ad spend? Enter the new numbers and see how they change your overhead per hour and overhead percentage. This prevents surprises when the bills start rolling in after you have already committed.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="font-heading font-bold text-2xl mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-lg">
            <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer text-text-primary font-medium hover:text-accent transition-colors">What are typical plumbing business overhead costs?</summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text-secondary text-sm leading-relaxed">Most plumbing businesses carry 25-35% overhead relative to revenue. The largest categories are usually fleet costs (fuel, insurance, payments at $1,000-$1,800 per van per month), payroll for non-tech staff (office, dispatch, owner salary), insurance (general liability, workers comp at 4-6% of payroll), and marketing. A three-van shop with an office typically runs $18,000-$26,000 per month in overhead before any plumber labor or job materials.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-lg">
            <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer text-text-primary font-medium hover:text-accent transition-colors">How do I calculate overhead per hour for plumbing?</summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text-secondary text-sm leading-relaxed">Divide your total annual overhead by the total billable hours your plumbers produce in a year. For example, if annual overhead is $280,000 and you have 3 plumbers each billing 768 hours per year (64 hours per month), your total billable hours are 2,304. Overhead per hour is $280,000 / 2,304 = $121.53. This number must be built into your hourly billing rate on top of labor cost and profit margin.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-lg">
            <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer text-text-primary font-medium hover:text-accent transition-colors">What percentage of revenue should go to overhead in plumbing?</summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text-secondary text-sm leading-relaxed">The target range for plumbing companies is 25-35% of revenue going to overhead. Below 25% usually means a lean operation or underinvestment in growth. Above 35% signals you may be overspending or underpricing. Marketing alone should be 6-8% of revenue for a stable business and 10-15% if you are actively growing. Fleet costs typically run 8-12% and insurance 4-6%.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-lg">
            <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer text-text-primary font-medium hover:text-accent transition-colors">How do I reduce plumbing business overhead?</summary>
            <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text-secondary text-sm leading-relaxed">Start by identifying your top three overhead categories. Common wins include renegotiating insurance annually, optimizing truck routes to cut fuel costs, switching to cloud-based dispatch software, cross-training office staff to eliminate redundant positions, and auditing subscriptions for unused services. Do not cut marketing below 6% of revenue or you will shrink your pipeline. Focus on efficiency gains rather than blanket cuts.</div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </Fragment>
</ToolLayout>

<script>
  function calculate() {
    // Facility
    const shopRent = parseFloat((document.getElementById('shopRent') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const utilities = parseFloat((document.getElementById('utilities') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const facilityTotal = shopRent + utilities;

    // Fleet
    const numTrucks = parseFloat((document.getElementById('numTrucks') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const fuelPerTruck = parseFloat((document.getElementById('fuelPerTruck') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const insurancePerTruck = parseFloat((document.getElementById('insurancePerTruck') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const maintPerTruck = parseFloat((document.getElementById('maintPerTruck') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const paymentPerTruck = parseFloat((document.getElementById('paymentPerTruck') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const fleetTotal = numTrucks * (fuelPerTruck + insurancePerTruck + maintPerTruck + paymentPerTruck);

    // Insurance
    const generalLiability = parseFloat((document.getElementById('generalLiability') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const workersComp = parseFloat((document.getElementById('workersComp') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const umbrella = parseFloat((document.getElementById('umbrella') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const insuranceTotal = generalLiability + workersComp + umbrella;

    // People
    const officeStaff = parseFloat((document.getElementById('officeStaff') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const dispatcher = parseFloat((document.getElementById('dispatcher') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const ownerSalary = parseFloat((document.getElementById('ownerSalary') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const bookkeeper = parseFloat((document.getElementById('bookkeeper') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const peopleTotal = officeStaff + dispatcher + ownerSalary + bookkeeper;

    // Operations
    const softwareDispatch = parseFloat((document.getElementById('softwareDispatch') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const answeringService = parseFloat((document.getElementById('answeringService') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const phoneInternet = parseFloat((document.getElementById('phoneInternet') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const toolsEquipment = parseFloat((document.getElementById('toolsEquipment') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const uniforms = parseFloat((document.getElementById('uniforms') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const operationsTotal = softwareDispatch + answeringService + phoneInternet + toolsEquipment + uniforms;

    // Compliance
    const plumbingLicense = parseFloat((document.getElementById('plumbingLicense') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const businessLicenses = parseFloat((document.getElementById('businessLicenses') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const backflowCerts = parseFloat((document.getElementById('backflowCerts') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const complianceTotal = plumbingLicense + businessLicenses + backflowCerts;

    // Marketing
    const onlineAds = parseFloat((document.getElementById('onlineAds') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const seoWebsite = parseFloat((document.getElementById('seoWebsite') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const printMail = parseFloat((document.getElementById('printMail') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const referralPrograms = parseFloat((document.getElementById('referralPrograms') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const marketingTotal = onlineAds + seoWebsite + printMail + referralPrograms;

    // Other
    const accountingLegal = parseFloat((document.getElementById('accountingLegal') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const badDebt = parseFloat((document.getElementById('badDebt') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const misc = parseFloat((document.getElementById('misc') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const otherTotal = accountingLegal + badDebt + misc;

    // Context
    const numTechs = parseFloat((document.getElementById('numTechs') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 1;
    const billableHours = parseFloat((document.getElementById('billableHours') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 1;
    const annualRevenue = parseFloat((document.getElementById('annualRevenue') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 0;
    const callsPerDay = parseFloat((document.getElementById('callsPerDay') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 1;
    const workingDays = parseFloat((document.getElementById('workingDays') as HTMLInputElement).value) || 1;

    // Totals
    const totalMonthly = facilityTotal + fleetTotal + insuranceTotal + peopleTotal + operationsTotal + complianceTotal + marketingTotal + otherTotal;
    const totalAnnual = totalMonthly * 12;
    const perTech = totalAnnual / numTechs;
    const perHour = totalAnnual / (numTechs * billableHours * 12);
    const perCall = totalAnnual / (callsPerDay * workingDays * 12);
    const overheadPct = annualRevenue > 0 ? (totalAnnual / annualRevenue) * 100 : 0;

    // Format currency
    const fmt = (n: number) => '$' + n.toLocaleString(undefined, { minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 0 });
    const fmtDec = (n: number) => '$' + n.toLocaleString(undefined, { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });

    // Primary results
    document.getElementById('result-monthly')!.textContent = fmt(totalMonthly);
    document.getElementById('result-annual')!.textContent = fmt(totalAnnual);
    document.getElementById('result-per-tech')!.textContent = fmt(perTech);
    document.getElementById('result-per-hour')!.textContent = fmtDec(perHour);
    document.getElementById('result-per-call')!.textContent = fmtDec(perCall);
    document.getElementById('result-pct')!.textContent = overheadPct.toFixed(1) + '%';

    // Color overhead percentage
    const pctEl = document.getElementById('result-pct')!;
    pctEl.classList.remove('text-[#34D399]', 'text-[#FBBF24]', 'text-[#EF4444]');
    if (overheadPct <= 25) {
      pctEl.classList.add('text-[#34D399]');
    } else if (overheadPct <= 35) {
      pctEl.classList.add('text-[#FBBF24]');
    } else {
      pctEl.classList.add('text-[#EF4444]');
    }

    // Category breakdown
    const categories = [
      { id: 'facility', total: facilityTotal },
      { id: 'fleet', total: fleetTotal },
      { id: 'insurance', total: insuranceTotal },
      { id: 'people', total: peopleTotal },
      { id: 'operations', total: operationsTotal },
      { id: 'compliance', total: complianceTotal },
      { id: 'marketing', total: marketingTotal },
      { id: 'other', total: otherTotal },
    ];

    categories.forEach(cat => {
      document.getElementById('cat-' + cat.id)!.textContent = fmt(cat.total);
      const barPct = totalMonthly > 0 ? (cat.total / totalMonthly) * 100 : 0;
      (document.getElementById('bar-' + cat.id) as HTMLElement).style.width = barPct + '%';
    });

    // Benchmark bar
    const clampedPct = Math.max(0, Math.min(100, overheadPct));
    const benchmarkBar = document.getElementById('benchmark-bar')!;
    benchmarkBar.style.width = Math.min(clampedPct, 60) / 60 * 100 + '%';
    benchmarkBar.classList.remove('bg-[#34D399]', 'bg-[#FBBF24]', 'bg-[#EF4444]');
    if (overheadPct <= 25) {
      benchmarkBar.classList.add('bg-[#34D399]');
    } else if (overheadPct <= 35) {
      benchmarkBar.classList.add('bg-[#FBBF24]');
    } else {
      benchmarkBar.classList.add('bg-[#EF4444]');
    }

    const yourPctEl = document.getElementById('benchmark-your-pct')!;
    yourPctEl.textContent = overheadPct.toFixed(1) + '%';
    yourPctEl.classList.remove('text-[#34D399]', 'text-[#FBBF24]', 'text-[#EF4444]');
    if (overheadPct <= 25) {
      yourPctEl.classList.add('text-[#34D399]');
    } else if (overheadPct <= 35) {
      yourPctEl.classList.add('text-[#FBBF24]');
    } else {
      yourPctEl.classList.add('text-[#EF4444]');
    }

    // Show/hide warning
    const warningEl = document.getElementById('benchmark-warning')!;
    if (overheadPct > 35) {
      warningEl.classList.remove('hidden');
    } else {
      warningEl.classList.add('hidden');
    }

  }


  // Auto-calculate on input change
  document.querySelectorAll('#overhead-calc input').forEach(el => {
    el.addEventListener('change', calculate);
    el.addEventListener('input', calculate);
  });

  // Calculate on load with defaults
  calculate();
</script>
